Introduction¶

Task: To find relationships between background checks, purchases, and population data subsets.

Starting and leading questions:

  • What census data is most associated with high gun per capita?
  • Which states have had the highest growth in gun registrations?
  • What is the overall trend of gun purchases?

The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isnt otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. The data has been supplemented with state level data from census.gov.

What is the NICS Process?

When a person tries to buy a firearm, the seller, known as a Federal Firearms Licensee (FFL), contacts NICS electronically or by phone. The prospective buyer fills out the ATF form, and the FFL relays that information to the NICS. The NICS staff performs a background check on the buyer. That background check verifies the buyer does not have a criminal record or isn't otherwise ineligible to purchase or own a firearm. Since launching in 1998, more than 300 million checks have been done, leading to more than 1.5 million denials.

The NICS data is found in one sheet of an .xlsx file. It contains the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type. The U.S. census data is found in a .csv file. It contains several variables at the state level. Most variables just have one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year.

The graph shows in the early years between 1999 to 2004, background checks with purchases were done at a constant level. Beyond that date, background check have been increasing and growing at a linear rate. However, in this trend, there are about two outliers, one around 2012-2013, andone around 2015-2016.

Conclusions¶

In reiteration:

  • What census data is most associated with high gun per capita?

We find, Kentucky, Texas, and California have the most firearm background checks done of all time from 1998-2017. Interestingly, while Kentucky, Texas, and California had the top three most checks done of all time, it is not the same against the population of the state. Kentucky had a higher number again, and Kentucky had a rate of doing background checks against its population of 0.0486848. Kentucky has done more background checks against its population than Texas and California. Texas had a proportion of 0.002585 and California had a proportion of 0.002168. While Utah is almost not even close to having a long record of doing background checks, it does a lot of checks against its population. Utah had a proportion of 0.039579. It must have a small population which makes the difference in giving it a high scoring proportion. Indeed, Utah has a small population in 2010 of '2,763,885' compared to a lot of the other states. Kentucky also has a small population compared to the others.

We find when we test more of the Census categories at random against the checks per state population, as shown in the scatterplots, the trends seem very similar. Indeed, the graphs are nearly identical with very minor differences to each other. We find that the one that is really different in trend is the Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander population. The data points are more clustered. However, this analysis is limited, as we only compared the 2010 official census when there are about 5 years of population differences. If we had time to use the 2016 population, we could find a difference. But even that is limited and possibly biased since it is an estimate and may not have had the same procedures in making as the official 2010 census count.

  • Which states have had the highest growth in gun registrations?

The graph we made shows, Kentucky having the most rapid growth. Interestingly, the state only really picks up at around 2006 and was nearly nonexistent prior to. North Carolina had a huge spike in around 2014. I wonder what that is about? It would be interesting to compare it to the country's mood, trends, and news. The states of North Carolina (besides the big bump), Illinois, and Michigan have been at a steady growth level that changes nearly at the same rate. This process is a bit limited, as machine learning would be needed to find the growth rate in registrations rather than estimate by a graph. Machine learning could find the best fit line to represent the graph and assign a number.

  • What is the overall trend of gun purchases?

The graph shows in the early years between 1999 to 2004, background checks with purchases were done at a constant level. Essentially people did the same number despite population growth. Beyond that period of time, background check has been increasing and growing at a linear rate. However, in this trend, there are about two outliers, one around 2012-2013, and one around 2015-2016. Again, it would be interesting to compare it to the country's mood, trends, and news to see why these are outliers.!
